metadata.name: Balancium #30
metadata.description:
"Balancium" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

In the fall of 1931, in Alexander Calder's studio, Marcel Duchamp coined the term 'mobile' for his kinetic sculptures. Later, Calder wrote: "This, in French, means not only 'movable'— but also a 'motive', 'a reason for an act' so I found it a very good word."
 
Around the same year, Bruno Munari started making colorful and whimsical mobiles. He called them "useless machines", existing without any purpose and inviting viewers to just look. Elements are connected with nearly invisible threads or wires, allowing the artist to create the illusion of shapes floating in the air.

Balancium is both a virtual mobile and a useless object. Generated by the code, it undergoes a continual transformation. The movement of the air, or invisible fluid, becomes an integral part of the design and amplifies serenity. 
 
There is a keyboard key that unlocks more variations.

metadata.name: SC.002 : Studies Series #51
metadata.description:
This hybrid project combines elements of 2 previous drops: Glomularus + Inertial Packing. The project is intended as a giveaway to show appreciation to the community of collectors who previously have minted my work.

SC.002 includes multiple constraint systems, based on Verlet and Euler Integration approaches, with attached geometric primitives and softbody Prototubes. Numerous user controls are included:

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
-, +: reduce | increase Node Count
{, }: reduce | increase Packing Dimension
c, v: reduce | increase Node Adhesion
h, j: reduce | increase Node Jitter
b, n: disable| enable Node-Node Collision
z, x: reduce | increase Stick Constraint
a, s: hide | show Nodes
q, w: hide | show Wireframe
d, f: reduce | increase Prototube Thickness
p: screen capture

Tip:
1. There are 8 unique geometries, should you be inclined to collect a full set.
2. Bringing values outside of "rational" range is encouraged.

Note:
Please post your favorite SC.002 screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: Pobbles #92
metadata.description:
The pobbles are generative blob-rocks: staring in silence, sometimes half-smiling, generally bored. 

• The pobbles are digital recreations of a series of rock-doodles by S.F.Kislev (my big brother). They are an attempt to capture a specific, singular handwriting, and evolve it using code. 
• See the original, 2014 handmade version here - https://pobbles.tez.page..
• Alternative titles considered include Peggles™, Plops™, Blobbies™, Floofs™, Flintstones™, Lardies™, Plumps™, Fats™ and Wet-Ones™. 
• The pobbles are written entirely in paper.js and p5.js. 
• The pobbles are an effort to take generative art into the realm of the cute. 
• They work well with toddlers.

🖨️ Collectors minting at the first auction tier receive a hand-crafted riso print of their pobble. Color variation between the file and the print will apply. 🖨️

metadata.name: Cables and Clouds #60
metadata.description:
Capturing clouds... an old dream of mad scientist... coming true...
But wait... are they real clouds ? Maybe... maybe not...
Is it the real life ?
Is this just fantasy ?

Interaction.
Press h in live mode to list the possibilities.
Key 's'  : Save an image of the output at the current resolution
Key 1-9 : Change resolution
Key 'c' to change color palette
Key 'd' to toggle a special color mode to highlight the different components (and have the number of points used in your specific drawing).

Features.
18 different features displayed (format, color palettes, main elements characteristics, rare elements...).

metadata.name: Altered #231
metadata.description:
Adj. Changed in character or composition, typically in a comparatively small but significant way.

Please note that the display is progressive and can take some time to finalize.

Artwork by Patrice Orenes-Lerma - @patxol - 2022
Made with math, love & p5js.
CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

Features include :

- 20 color palettes (10 standard, 10 rare)
- 8 palette progression types
- 3 aspect ratio (Portrait is standard, 1:1 and landscape are rare)
- 8 Alteration types
- 3 Alteration power levels
- 5 types of symmetry
- 3 densities
- Spaced mode and Sharp mode

metadata.name: Colored Elementary Cellular Automaton #63
metadata.description:
The algorithm is based on Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton. 
This is a 1D cellular automaton with a neighborhood of 5 cells. This gives us 2^5 = 32 patterns for a neighborhood and 2^32 = 4.29B possible combinations!!! The size of the cell varies in a range of 2 to 8. There is a 15% of getting a black and white art.

Pattern rarity:
- Pattern 1 _25%
- Pattern 2 _30%
- Pattern 3 _35%
- Pattern 4 _15%

Note: The art might look in different resolutions because of the responsive view, but the color, pattern, and layout remain the same.

metadata.name: Kintsugi #178
metadata.description:
Kintsugi is a philosophy, it's the concept of highlighting imperfections, visualizing patches and seams on the area to focus on, rather than focusing on missing details.

This art of precious scars is a technique used as a means of analyzing the idea of ​​loss through synthesis and restoration of the destroyed and a metaphor for the possibility of rebirth.
Recovery from destructive events is possible through care and patching, not through hiding the damage, but by accepting a new state of the object or the whole life.
The world is a vase that is endlessly disassembled and sewn together again, continuing to bear traces of each event.

Non-human entities helped us put these vases together. In the beginning, there were vague forms, these were the shards themselves, created in collaboration with Latent Diffusion. Over time, they have grown in detail, drawing their stories more clearly, thanks to Jax Diffusion.

The code that puts everything together was written by Yulikolay, for which he is greatly appreciated.
